
🔐 1. Ethical Hacking Lifecycle
Ethical hacking follows a systematic process to identify and fix vulnerabilities.

Phases:

1. Reconnaissance (Information Gathering)
• Collect target information
• Types:
◇ Passive (no direct interaction)
◇ Active (direct probing)

2. Scanning
◇ Identify live systems, ports, services
◇ Tools: Nmap, Hping , nessus

3. Gaining Access (Exploitation)
◇ Exploit vulnerabilities
◇ Example: SQL Injection, buffer overflow


4. Maintaining Access
◇ Install backdoors, persistence
◇ Example: Trojans, rootkits


5. Covering Tracks
◇ Delete logs, hide activity


🧑‍💻 2. Types of Hackers

1. White Hat (Ethical Hackers)
◇ Work legally to secure systems

2. Black Hat
◇ Malicious attackers

3. Grey Hat
◇ Between legal and illegal

4. Script Kiddies
◇ Use pre-built tools

5. Hacktivists
◇ Political/social motives

6. State-Sponsored Hackers
◇ Government-backed

7. Insider Threats
◇ Employees misusing access


