Nessus

🔍 Nessus Tool – Full Theory (Vulnerability Scanner)

🧠 1. What is Nessus?
Nessus is a popular vulnerability assessment tool developed by Tenable.
It is used to:
• Identify security vulnerabilities
• Detect misconfigurations
• Find outdated software
• Check compliance issues

👉 In simple words:
 Nessus scans systems and tells you “where you are weak” before hackers find it.

🎯 2. Purpose of Nessus
◇ Vulnerability Assessment (VA)
◇ Risk management
◇ Compliance auditing (PCI-DSS, ISO, etc.)
◇ Patch verification
◇ Network security auditing


🔄 3. How Nessus Works (Architecture)

Components:
1. Nessus Server
◇ Runs scans
◇ Stores results

• Nessus Client (Web Interface)
◇ Browser-based dashboard (https://localhost:8834)

• Plugins
◇ Core of Nessus (like scripts)
◇ Each plugin checks a specific vulnerability


⚙️ 4. Types of Scans in Nessus

🔹 Host Discovery Scan
 ◇ Finds live systems in network


🔹 2. Basic Network Scan
◇ Default scan
◇ Detects open ports, services, vulnerabilities

🔹 3. Advanced Scan
◇ Custom scan settings (ports, plugins, timing)

🔹 4. Credentialed Scan
◇ Uses login (SSH/Windows creds)
◇ Deep scan (very accurate)

🔹 5. Web Application Scan
◇ Checks websites for vulnerabilities

🔍 5. Nessus Scan Phases
1. Target Identification
2. Port Scanning
3. Service Detection
4. Vulnerability Detection (via plugins)
5. Report Generation

🧪 6. Types of Vulnerabilities Detected
◇ 🔓 Open ports (e.g., 21, 22, 80)
◇ 🐞 Software bugs
◇ ⚠️ Misconfigurations
◇ 🔑 Weak passwords
◇ 🕳️ Web vulnerabilities (XSS, SQLi)
◇ 📦 Missing patches


🧰 7. Nessus Plugins (Very Important)
◇ Thousands of plugins
◇ Written in NASL (Nessus Attack Scripting Language)


Plugin categories:
◇ Windows vulnerabilities
◇ Linux vulnerabilities
◇ Databases
◇ Web servers
◇ Network devices

👉 Example:
◇ Plugin checks if Apache version is outdated


📊 8. Severity Levels in Nessus

| Severity | Meaning |
| 🔴 Critical | Immediate threat |
| 🟠 High | Serious risk |
| 🟡 Medium | Moderate |
| 🔵 Low | Minor |
| ⚪ Info | Informational |




📄 9. Nessus Reports
After scan, Nessus generates reports:

Includes:
◇ Vulnerability name
◇ Description
◇ Risk level
◇ CVE ID
◇ Solution (fix)
◇ Affected systems

👉 Formats:
◇ PDF
◇ HTML
◇ CSV


🔐 10. Credentialed vs Non-Credentialed Scan

🔹 Non-Credentialed
◇ External scan
◇ Less accurate
◇ Like hacker view


🔹 Credentialed
◇ Internal scan
◇ Uses login access
◇ Very accurate


🌐 11. Nessus vs Other Tools

| Tool | Purpose |
| Nmap | Port scanning |
| OpenVAS | Open-source Nessus alternative |
| Metasploit | Exploitation |
| Nessus | Vulnerability scanning |



👉 Nessus = Find weaknesses
 👉 Metasploit = Exploit weaknesses

